how twenty-first century political struggles over immigration, LGBTQ rights, reproductive justice, and police violence have created a sense of vulnerability that has an impact on culture and the law. By researching organizations like the Minutemen (civilians who monitor the US/Mexico border), the Protect Marriage Coalition (a campaign to ban same-sex marriage in California), and the Center for Bio-Ethical Reform (an anti-abortion movement), Katie Oliviero shows how conservative movements use the rhetoric of risk to oppose liberal policies by claiming that the nation, family, and morality are imperiled and in need of government protection.The author argues that this sensationalism has shifted the focus away from the everyday and institutional precarities experienced by marginalized communities and instead reinforces the idea that groups only deserve social justice protections when their beliefs reflect the dominant nationalist, racial, and sexual ideals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConservatismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aLiberalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMarginality, SocialzUnited States. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited States. 0aSocial actionzUnited States. 0aSocial justicezUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited States. 0aSocial valueszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  a#BlackLivesMatter.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aBodies: The Exhibition.  aCenter for Bio-Ethical Reform.  aGonzales v. Carhart.  aLGBTQ rights.  aMinutemen.  aProtect Marriage Coalition.  aTRAP legislation.  aYes on Proposition 8.  aabortion.  aambivalence.  aantidemocratic.  aantidiscrimination.  abiopolitics.  abodily irrefutability.  achildren of color.  acoalition.  aconservative movements.  acorpse and corporeality.  